04428nam a22005775i 9780813570969DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20162016nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2015032496  a97808135709697 a10.36019/97808135709692doi  a(DE-B1597)526440  a(OCoLC)957465359  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aGV1060.73b.C59 2016 7aSPO0000002bisacsh04a796.42/572231 aCohen, Diana Tracy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIron Dads :bManaging Family, Work, and Endurance Sport Identities /cDiana Tracy Cohen. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (210 p.) :b3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Sport and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations And Definitions -- t1. Taking The First Step -- t2. Inside Triathlon Culture -- t3. To Tri Or Not To Try -- t4. The Juggling Act -- t5. Why Class Matters -- t6. Faith Meets 140.6 -- t7. Th Rowing In The Towel -- t8. The Road Ahead -- tAppendix: Methodological Reflections -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout The Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong the most difficult athletic events a person can attempt, the iron-distance triathlon—a 140.6 mile competition—requires an intense prerace training program. This preparation can be as much as twenty hours per week for a full year leading up to a race. In Iron Dads, Diana Tracy Cohen focuses on the pressures this extensive preparation can place on families, exploring the ways in which men with full-time jobs, one or more children, and other responsibilities fit this level of training into their lives. An accomplished triathlete as well as a trained social scientist, Cohen offers much insight into the effects of endurance-sport training on family, parenting, and the sense of self. She conducted in-depth interviews with forty-seven iron-distance competitors and three prominent men in the race industry, and analyzed triathlon blog postings made by Iron Dads. What sacrifices, Cohen asks, are required—both at home and at work—to cross the iron-distance finish line? What happens when work, family, and sport collide? Is it possible for fathers to meet their own parenting expectations while pursuing such a time-consuming regimen? With the tensions of family economics, how do you justify spending $5,000 on a racing bike? At what point does sport become work? Cohen discovered that, by fostering family involvement in this all-consuming effort, Iron Dads are able to maintain a sense of themselves not only as strong, masculine competitors, but also as engaged fathers. Engagingly written and well researched, Iron Dads provides a penetrating, firsthand look at extreme endurance sports, including practical advice for aspiring racers and suggestions for making triathlons more family-friendly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aEndurance sportsxPsychological aspects. 0aFathersxFamily relationships. 0aFathersxPsychology. 0aTriathletesxFamily relationships. 0aTriathletesxPsychology. 0aTriathlonxPsychological aspects. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066614440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081357096940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813570969423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813570969/original  a978-3-11-066614-4  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles